In stating that I was leery, I was remembering what I had read about the
Barry paternity case in John McCabe's biography of Chaplin titled &quot;Charlie
Chaplin&quot; (Doubleday, 1978):

&quot;[A] blood test showed that Joan Barry's was A, [daughter] Carol Ann's was
B, and Chaplin's O, thus making it impossible for him to be the father of
the child. But the presiding judge ruled that the 'ends of justice' would be
best served by a 'full and fair trial of the issues.' Since the key issue
had already been medically determined, this thinking would seem to be rather
clouded. Chaplin, in any case, was placed on trial, which ended in a hung
jury voting seven to five for acquittal. A mistrial being declared, a second
trial began April 12, 1944. [end of page 206]

&quot;Chaplin had retained for his defense Charles A. 'Pat' Millikan, a
straightforward, no-nonsense lawyer, who was sure that the undisputed
medical evidence would acquit his client. Millikan did not count on the
presence on the other side of Joseph Scott, a jury of the old school.  Joan
Barry's first lawyer, on hearing the results of the blood test, withdrew
from the case [!!! take notice of that first lawyer's reaction !!!], but
Scott, a prominent old counselor who had the reputation of putting love of
church and country before all else, forgot the former as he nursed the
latter in spasms of outraged patriotism. [...]

&quot;The Scott histrionics won the day. The jury was out for three hours and
returned with an eleven-to-one decision against Chaplin. The judge ruled
that Chaplin must pay seventy-five dollars a week for Carol Ann until she
was twenty-one. This was done.&quot; [page 207]

Whatever the rules were in California about the weight that could or should
be placed on the results of blood tests in determining paternity in
California courts in 1944, the above passage indicates that the lawyers (on
both sides) expected the blood test results to be introduced and discussed
in the proceedings.  Furthermore, I recall another full-fledged bio that
reported that when Chaplin moved for there to be blood test results as
evidence, he was informed that if any blood samples were taken from the
mother and the child, then those results and Chaplin's too must be provided
to the prosecution, regardless of whose side would be substantiated by the
three-part results.  The account goes on to say that because Chaplin had a
blood type that could result in a baby with blood types other than his, he
was taking a bigger chance than the average person that the results would
make him a &quot;maybe&quot; or a &quot;match&quot; rather than someone ruled out as
possibility.  Nonetheless, Chaplin took the risk by ordering the tests.  His
losing the case despite medical evidence that was statistically-unexpected
made the verdict all the more a miscarriage of justice.

The American Heritage article would have readers believe that blood tests
were inadmissable and thus the jury never heard about them.

--
David Hayes

