I spend a lot of time looking at 1860 -1920 census, and I dont find
May-September marriages all that unusual  for that time period at
all.  Although most seem to be female 16-18, male 26-32 range.
My speculation is that  usually two things account for this, first the
male is generally establishing himself in a profession,  and second
that this is his second marriage (the first usually being deceased -
in those days before antibiotics).

I do note that I have seen fudging upward of the female's age in the
census at times, usually for those who should be 18 and already have 2
children or so (and for those wondering, I estimate the correct age on
the birthyear as reported by their parent in the previous census, and
not on just their ages 20-30 years later).   While not uncommon to be
married at 15 or so,  i'm guessing it was frowned on even then.

(this writer should note that he recalls that his home state had the
legal age for females to marry in the 1950s-early 1960s was 13! with
males 14, with parental permission.  I vaguely recall without parental
consent is was 16).

